at night the brightest light 
shining in this south america city of 10 million is cast by the moon 
spotlights on public monuments the flashing neon glare of 
billboards lights in office towers store windows and even on a 
christmas tree near a main thoroughfare have been turned down or 
even off by government order 
there is an electricity shortage 
streetlights have been dimmed by 50 percent drivers who usually 
careen along narrow often cobblestone streets downtown with only 
their cars parking lights have taken to turning on low beams 
the problem stems from seasonally low levels of water in the 
uruguay limay and neuquen rivers that feed hydroelectric stations 
and the shutdown for repairs or maintenance of argentinas two 
nuclear power plants 
the system is working at the limit of its capacity and we 
should be prepared for whatever eventuality and are running the risk 
of a total outage said daniel larriqueta a spokesman for the 
interior ministry 
portenos as residents of this port city are called have had to 
make do with rotating scheduled outages of five hours a day since 
last week 
city residents have become accustomed to summertime electricity 
shortages as the city has grown faster than its public services can 
handle blackouts which have occurred half a dozen times since 
1965 are relatively rare however the last occurred in november 
1985 
the latest scheduled outages have meant walking up flights of 
stairs for lack of working elevators sweating in late spring heat 
for lack of air conditioning and dodging four five and sometimes 
six lanes of cars at rush hour for lack of functioning traffic 
signals 
beginning today the hours of the three governmentcontrolled 
television stations in this capital city will be cut back to 12 
hours noon to midnight the two private stations have been 
requested by the government to do likewise 
the usual hours of operation are 7 am to 3 am 
nighttime events like horseracing at the hipodromo and concerts 
have been canceled until further notice unless the facility has its 
own source of electricity soccer games usually played at night to 
avoid daytime heat have been rescheduled for the afternoon 
at the huge salto grande hydroelectric complex on the uruguay 
