a consent decree may be reached by the end of 
the week for the cleanup of a federally owned uranium enrichment 
plant in ohio a us energy department official says 
an agreement to clean up the portsmouth gaseous diffusion plant 
near piketon in southern ohio was announced last month by ohio gov 
richard celeste and state attorney general anthony j celebrezze jr 
however the plan still was under review by the energy department 
on monday spokesman douglas g elmets said 
a senior department official who asked that he not be 
identified said the energy department may have a decision by the 
end of the week on a consent decree that would involve court 
supervision of a cleanup 
when celeste and celebrezze announced the 50 million cleanup 
plan last month they said it was significant because the federal 
agency would be bound by state law and regulation 
the piketon plant processes uranium for fuel for commercial 
nuclear power reactors it generates toxic wastes such as 
polychlorinated biphenyls or pcbs solvents and metals as well as 
radioactive materials 
when the agreement was announced nov 22 celeste said he hoped 
it would serve as a model for other tough cleanup cases such as the 
governmentowned fernald plant near cincinnati environmental 
officials say that plant has dumped radioactive waste improperly 
possibly contaminating ground water since it began processing 
uranium for nuclear weapons in 1951 
the piketon plan calls for the energy department to be subject to 
orders issued by the ohio environmental protection agency which 
would supervise the cleanup of about 6 million pounds of waste last 
month officials said the agreement still needed to be incorporated 
into a federal court consent decree 
