<TEXT>
large airlines at four major airports would 
have to prove they make heavy use of their takeoff and landing slots 
or risk losing them to other carriers under a proposed federal rule 
change 
the proposal released monday by the federal aviation 
administration would revise the high density rule at chicago 
ohare international laguardia and kennedy international in new 
york and washington national 
the rule adopted in 1969 limits the number of takeoff and 
landing slots at the airports during heavy traffic periods 
currently airlines must show that they are using those slots during 
65 percent of the heavy traffic hours over a twomonth period 
the new proposal would require large air carriers with 10 or more 
slots to show that the slots are being used at a 90 percent rate or 
the faa would consider withdrawing them the requirement would be 80 
percent for carriers with five to nine slots and would stay at 65 
percent for all others 
the slots that are taken away from an airline could then be 
available for sale or reallocation to a different airline the faa 
said 
the change would increase opportunity for new entrant carriers 
to have access to highdensity airports and for small incumbent 
carriers to increase the number of operations at those airports 
the faa said in a statement 
american airlines spokesman al becker said his company was 
encouraged that the faa wanted to make sure the takeoff and 
landing slots are fully utilized 
were using every single slot we have becker said at some 
airports we obviously could use more he said that in some cases 
airlines have held their slots without fully using them 
the limits on takeoff and landing slots are necessary because an 
airports air traffic control system has limited capacity becker 
said 
we are not in favor of any slot program at all if it can be 
avoided becker said but eliminating the system would require 
costly expansion of the air traffic control systems 
the faa is seeking public and aircraft industry comments on its 
proposal 
</TEXT>
