a mailorder catalog firm that has 
begun catering to the captive audience of prisoners reports 
christmas sales are on the rise 
they are very good customers and its developed into a 
substantial segment of our business where else are they going to 
go said mortimer polep chairman of the holyokebased paysaver 
catalog showrooms inc 
we even got a thankyou letter from one inmate who said after 
all our money is as good as the guy that hasnt been caught yet 
he said 
paul hahn of the 2000member national mail order association 
based in los angeles said its impossible to tell how many inmates 
order from catalogs but sales seem to be up everywhere 
we dont keep any special statistics on sales to prison 
inmates but my sense is that they have been increasing as prisons 
have eased the regulations on what kinds of packages prisoners can 
receive he said 
polep said his companys christmas sales to prisoners are up 25 
percent this year but he wont divulge exactly how big his business 
is behind bars 
at the 1100inmate state prison at norfolk sgt christopher 
cameron said he inspects about 30 packages a day that inmates have 
ordered from catalogs we dont allow them anything like hacksaws 
or shotguns he said 
for the three weeks before christmas however the prison 
suspends its rules against mailed food and allows inmates to receive 
packages up to 25 pounds holding mailorder and homemade delicacies 
to inspect the food packages the prison must hold up inspections 
of other packages which wait until after christmas to reach inmates 
the food is more important and meaningful to them anyway 
cameron said they can get clothes all year 
the largest purveyors to the norfolk prisoners are cook brothers 
an illinoisbased catalog firm specializing in lowcost items 
followed by service merchandise of nashville tenn and 
merchandising giants jc penney co and sears roebuck and co 
cameron said 
clothing is the big sales item at the mediumsecurity prison 
followed by towels television sets radios and fans he said 
weve put together a little booklet on what they can order but 
essentially its any basic necessity cameron said they know by 
word of mouth that if there were any problems with anyone trying to 
bring in weapons or drugs we would cut back on the orders and we 
can trace it right back to who is responsible 
payments are made by the prison against inmate accounts he said 
they build up accounts by working in prison or by getting money 
from their families 
