<DOCNO> AP881220-0082 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
press freedom came under attack in 1988 from some 
of its staunchest defenders democratic countries such as the 
united states britain india and australia the international press 
institute reported 
the plight of the media remained bleak under repressive regimes 
but the trend in democrcies was the years most worrisome 
development the institute said in its annual world press freedom 
review 
one of the saddest truths facing the media around the world 
today is the growing trend toward government interference in 
democratic countries peter galliner the institutes director 
wrote in the reports introduction 
the hopes and encouragement of nations which are on their way 
towards more freedom and who rely on an example from countries with 
a democratic system an open society and freedom must not be 
crushed by governments in the free world he said 
the 32page report cited significant improvements in press 
freedom in taiwan and south korea and setbacks in chile colombia 
malaysia and other nations where journalism continues to be a 
sometimes dangerous and often difficult profession 
while the soviet unions policy of glasnost has meant 
heartening strides toward a more open press restrictions on the 
reporting of subjects such as ethnic violence in armenia have been a 
disgrace the report said 
the institute which has offices in london and zurich is an 
independent body representing 2000 publishers and editors in more 
than 60 countries its report this year detailed developments in 82 
countries 
in 1988 the us administration continued its efforts to limit 
public access to information held by the american government the 
report said 
it cited as a blatant example of interference in the media 
the us supreme courts upholding of the conviction of a former 
intelligence analyst for giving satellite photographs of a soviet 
ship to a british magazine the analyst samuel loring morison was 
sentenced to two years in prison 
the report also criticized the new canadaus free trade 
agreement for restricting canadian journalists who can work in the 
united states to those with a university degree and three years 
experience 
attempts to define qualifications for journalists pose a 
serious threat it said noting it was the first time the rule was 
enshrined in an international accord 
in britain the press scored a victory when prime minister 
margaret thatchers government lost its court fight to prevent 
newspapers from publishing extracts from spycatcher the memoirs 
of former intelligence agent peter wright 
however the report criticized britains ban on all radio and 
television interviews with 11 groups in northern ireland including 
the outlawed irish republican army and its political wing sinn 
fein the report called the ban the most drastic action taken 
against british broadcasters in peacetime 
prime minister rajiv gandhi of india was forced at the last 
minute to withdraw legislation that would have shifted the duty of 
proving defamation from plaintiffs to journalists the report said 
an australian court ordered a journalist to reveal his sources 
and south africas press had an appalling year marked by 
threemonth publication bans for two newspapers and a onemonth ban 
on another it said 
elsewhere the media under dictatorships remained all too 
predictably under lock and key the report noted 
one of the worst years ever for the independent press in chile 
was marked by violent assaults on 24 foreign and chilean 
journalists five journalists were forced to leave colombia 
following the passage of an antiterrorist law 
jordan and malaysia cracked down on their press singapore 
continued to do so and china soured a promising start by reasserting 
control and suppressing negative news the report said 
however the south korean press had a watershed year with 
many visible and invisible restrictions lifted and in taiwan 
economic and political liberalizations were extended to the media 
the report said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

