the washedup medical waste and other debris 
that spoiled new york cityarea beaches last summer came from 
several sources including a landfill sewer overflows garbage 
transfer stations and storm water outlets state officials say 
we have not found any evidence of a single culprit discharging 
the medical waste environmental conservation commissioner thomas 
jorling said as he released a report on an investigation into the 
waste 
several of the states most popular beaches had to be closed 
temporarily during the areas hottest summer in decades when debris 
including syringes and blood vials came ashore waste washups 
also resulted in beach closings in other eastern states including 
new jersey and rhode island as well as along lake erie and lake 
michigan 
the report blamed the washups primarily on inadequate garbage 
handling in new york city and on the weather 
medical waste accounted for only 1 percent to 10 percent of the 
washed up debris jorling said monday the highly publicized beach 
closings pointed to the need for more stringent controls on all 
garbage including medical waste 
the report highlights the need for change in new york citys 
sewage and landfill systems said a spokesman for a national 
environmental organization 
while an army of state federal and local people have been 
looking for midnight dumpers the real villain here may actually be 
the city sewer system and the citys landfills said mark izeman 
of the natural resources defense council 
while much of the beach waste probably was disposed of legally 
environmental officials still believe the vials of blood that washed 
ashore could have been the result of illegal dumping said jorling 
the vials at least one of which contained blood contaminated by the 
aids virus are the subject of a criminal investigation he said 
the state and new york city have strengthened garbage policies 
and improved facilities since the beach closings said jorling 
