<TEXT>
the economy expanded at a moderate 25 percent 
pace during the julyseptember quarter the government reported 
tuesday but analysts said growth was rebounding and the federal 
reserve board probably will nudge interest rates higher as a result 
the commerce department said growth of the gross national 
product the broadest measure of economic health slowed during the 
third quarter from 30 percent in the 2nd quarter and 34 percent in 
the first three months of the year 
the gnp after adjusting for inflation rose 242 billion to an 
annual rate of 401 trillion in the third quarter 
the gnp figure for the third quarter the slowest expansion pace 
since the final quarter of 1986 was a slight downward revision from 
a preliminary estimate of 26 percent issued a month ago most 
economists had been looking for a slight upward adjustment 
the trend should be good news for federal reserve policy makers 
who want to curb economic growth to a range of 2 percent to 25 
percent which they believe is sustainable without increasing 
inflation 
however the government said the temporary effects of the summer 
drought which shriveled crops and seared pastures are masking the 
true strength of the economy in the final nine months of the year 
drought losses of 123 billion reduced the gnp growth rate by 
09 percentage points in the second quarter 05 percentage points 
in the third and will knock more than 10 percent off of fourth 
quarter rate 
the growth rate in the final three months of this year excluding 
the effects of the drought will top 3 percent most economists 
believe in the first half of next year assuming a return to normal 
farm production the economy will be expanding at a rate between 3 
percent and 4 percent they say 
what youre left with is an economy that is growing too fast to 
be acceptable to the federal reserve said robert g dederick an 
economist with northern trust co in chicago 
fed members fear that a gnp growth rate higher than the target 
range will strain factory capacity leading to shortages and 
resulting price increases also by boosting employment the growth 
encourages employers to bid up wages the feds cure is higher 
interest rates designed to make it more expensive for consumers and 
businesses to spend 
the fed began nudging interest rates higher in late march 
capping a series of tightening moves in august with a rise in the 
discount rate the interest it charges on loans to member banks 
when economic statistics for october and november made it clear 
that growth remained robust the fed responded last week by bumping 
up the federal funds rate the rate banks charge each other for 
overnight loans by a quarter of a percentage point to a range of 8 
percent to 8 percent 
david jones an economist with aubrey g lanston amp co a 
government securities dealer in new york said the next tightening 
move likely will come in the first two weeks of next month with 
another quarter point rise in the federal funds rate 
i think the fed will have to lean somewhat against those 
strong growth winds with a series of modest tightening steps 
but it will delay raising the discount rate if anything the fed 
is in danger of underreacting 
however other economists noting that consumer prices are rising 
at a 44 percent annual rate in 1988 the same as last year say 
inflation fears are overstated 
what were afraid of is the federal reserve will get carried 
away next year and raise interest rates too high and keep them too 
high too long said david wyss an economist with data resources 
inc a forecasting firm in lexington mass we might end up with 
a recession in late 1989 or early 1990 
but dederick and jones noted that a gnp price index which 
measures price increases in what americans are producing as opposed 
to what they are buying shot up at an annual rate of 53 percent in 
the third quarter the biggest jump in six years that was up from a 
50 percent rate in the second quarter 
in an accompanying report the commerce department said corporate 
profits after taxes advanced 39 percent in the third quarter after 
soaring 89 percent in the second quarter an earlier estimate 
which did not take into account profits by overseas subsidiaries of 
us corporations had said third quarter profits rose only a slight 
02 percent 
