<TEXT>
the international committee of the red 
cross withdrew its 17member staff in lebanon on tuesday after the 
workers received death threats 
the swiss delegates left moslem west beirut for the christian 
eastern sector then boarded a ferry for larnaca cyprus said 
police in the christian port of jounieh north of beirut they will 
fly to switzerland on wednesday 
in geneva the allswiss organization said it had suspended its 
humanitarian operations in lebanon after hearing monday that 
serious threats had been made against its delegates on mission in 
lebanon placing their lives in acute danger 
the icrc therefore feels compelled to suspend its entire 
humanitarian operation there and to repatriate all its expatriate 
staff immediately a red cross statement said 
tuesdays action by the red cross marked the first time in the 
more than 100year history of the organization that delegates were 
withdrawn because of threats on their lives 
a committee spokesman carlos bauverd declined to say how the 
death threats were received and what group was believed behind them 
the decision came four days after kidnappers released the chief 
red cross delegate in south lebanon peter winkler who was held 
hostage for nearly a month 
the kidnapping nov 16 prompted the red cross to scale down its 
presence in lebanon after 20 years of operations in the strifetorn 
country ten of the organizations 27 delegates left but 17 
remained 
upon winklers release red cross officials in geneva said the 
staff would soon be increased again and regular activities resumed 
the communique said the committee was ready to resume its 
operations in lebanon as soon as the threats are clearly and 
unequivocally withdrawn 
a rumor circulated in geneva that the threats had been phoned to 
the swedish ambassador in damascus rolf gauffin 
gauffin was an intermediary in the contacts that preceded 
winklers release in those contacts his kidnappers identified 
themselves as members of a group called the organization of 
socialist revolution 
swiss authorities said winklers captors tried to tie his release 
to a lenient sentence for a shiite lebanese hijacker hussein 
hariri who is to go on trial at the swiss supreme court feb 20 
swiss foreign minuister rene felber said switzerland had refused any 
concessions 
hariri hijacked an air afrique jetliner to geneva july 14 1987 
and killed a french passenger before he was overpowered and 
arrested he faces up to life imprisonment 
the swiss made up the largest western community remaining in west 
beirut after waves of kidnappings assassinations and civil war 
violence forced tens of thousands of foreigners to flee lebanon in 
the last 13 years 
police said the new exodus left less than 24 westerners living in 
west beirut 
fifteen foreign hostages are now being held in lebanon they 
include nine americans three britons an irishman an italian and a 
belgian 
the longest held is terry anderson chief middle east 
correspondent for the associated press who was kidnapped march 16 
1985 
red cross delegates operate in about 80 countries worldwide 
visiting prisoners and detainees and providing food and medical 
relief to civilian victims of armed conflict 
their work is primarily based on the 1949 geneva conventions on 
the protection of prisoners and civilians in time of war 
