the number of americans behind in their 
mortgage payments fell in the julyseptember quarter to the lowest 
levels in a year an organization of lenders said tuesday 
the mortgage bankers association of america said 473 percent of 
the payments on the 108 million mortgages surveyed in the third 
quarter were at least 30 days late 
it was the lowest rate since the third quarter of 1987 when 471 
percent of the mortgage payers were behind the rate a year ago was 
the lowest in eight years in the second quarter the delinquency 
rate was 490 percent 
the foreclosure rate edged down to 026 percent in the third 
quarter compared with 027 percent in the second quarter 
warren lasko executive vice president of the association said 
he was very heartened by the decline but the report noted a 
mixed pattern regionally 
in north central states the delinquency rate was 488 percent 
down from 530 percent a year ago the rate in the northeast was 
unchanged from a year ago at 412 percent the lowest of four 
regions 
however the rate in the south rose from 525 percent last year 
to 529 percent the rate in the west was 428 percent in the third 
quarter up from 410 percent a year ago 
a high employment level in the united states generally has helped 
keep delinquencies low the south has had a relatively high rate 
because texas and other southwestern states are struggling with a 
depressed oil industry 
two offsetting trends will affect delinquencies next year 
interest rates are rising increasing the monthly payments on 
adjustablerate mortgages however the economy is expected to 
remain strong at least through midyear keeping the unemployment 
rate low 
