a halfmillion children died last year 
because their third world countries slashed social welfare spending 
when faced with unprecedented debt unicef said tuesday in its 
annual report 
james p grant unicef executive director urged leaders of 
industrialized and developing nations to convene a summit to deal 
with the crisis 
he made the appeal in unicefs annual report the state of the 
worlds children which he formally released at a new delhi news 
conference telecast live to 40 nations 
the 500000 children he mentioned represented only a fraction of 
the child deaths in 1987 recorded by the un childrens fund 
three million children died last year because they didnt have 
50 cents worth of vaccine in them grant said half these deaths 
occurred in south asia 
among a few bright spots he highlighted were vaccination programs 
in two wartorn countries 
in el salvador and in lebanon in the midst of war they have 
been able to stop the war long enough to immunize their children 
he said 
failure to vaccinate children results not only from the debt 
crises but from war ignorance lack of health workers and rugged 
terrains isolating people from medical care 
grant said that for children these were the best and worst of 
times 
they are the worst of times because after 35 years of progress 
a significant percentage of mankind 900 million people is now 
sliding backward into poverty he said 
its the best of times because lowcost ways of preventing 
childrens deaths are becoming increasingly available 
these methods include vaccination against diseases such as 
measles tetanus and whooping cough others are oral rehydration 
programs using inexpensive salt solutions that combat diarrhea 
chief killer of small children in many impoverished nations 
one of the most alarming trends he noted was that 16 nations made 
less progress against child mortality last year than they were 
making a decade ago because their debtburdened governments have had 
to cut back on social spending 
by far the heaviest consequences are being borne by the 
children said grant for these 16 countries alone the number 
of child deaths in the last 12 months is approximately 650000 more 
than would have been the case if the 197080 rate of decline in 
underfive mortality had continued 
the 16 nations cited by unicef are argentina brazil chile 
costa rica cuba ecuador haiti jamaica mexico panama in the 
western hemisphere and benin botswana liberia madagascar nigeria 
and togo in africa 
