<TEXT>
credit playwright charles fuller with setting up 
an ambitious project for himself a cycle of five plays dealing 
with the black experience in the united states from the civil war to 
the turn of the century 
but his ambitions have gotten the best of him at least in the 
first two of these historical dramas called sally and 
prince which arrived over the weekend at offbroadways negro 
ensemble company 
the plays both set during the civil war are sketchy historical 
melodramas long on plot and short on poetry or power they 
reiterate the same themes particularly about freedom or the lack of 
it for blacks first under the slavemasters of the old south and 
then under the economic overlords of the north the plays say they 
traded one serfdom for another 
the subject is discussed early on in sally which had its 
world premiere last summer in atlanta at the national black arts 
festival despite its title the play deals mostly with a group of 
black union soldiers who are forced to take a pay cut and earn less 
than their white counterparts 
some are defiant and pay the price with their lives others 
accept it and pay a different kind of penalty one who acquiesces is 
prince logan an ambitious black soldier who is the most interesting 
character in both plays his dilemma to follow the army or revel 
in his newly won freedom merits most of your attention 
it is princes survival that fuller chronicles in these two 
dramas and i suspect the man will turn up in other plays in this 
series you dont need to see both of the first two dramas to 
understand his character but it helps samuel l jacksons 
persuasive even noble performance as prince also helps its a 
portrayal that deepens in the second play as fuller tries to deal 
with the dislocation and disorientation of the newly freed slaves 
these intentions get sidetracked by a lot of peripheral events 
directed by douglas turner ward and acted by the rest of the large 
cast at a feverish pace there are plenty of gunshots a stabbing or 
two and some heavyhanded attempts at sexual humor the dialogue is 
often flat more concerned with recounting events than illuminating 
character 
consider the first play the weaker of the two evenings of drama 
although she is the title character sally remains the most elusive 
person on stage tragic things happen to her her husband is 
poisoned her son is killed by rebel troops her affair with prince 
ends malevolently but throughout her troubles we never get to 
know the woman michelle shay a fine actress is stymied by the 
underwritten role 
another good performer hattie winston has a better time of it 
in prince where she plays lu an indominable camp follower who 
also manages to live and profit through the war 
in prince the focus switches from military to civilian the 
exslaves who have to work the cotton fields for new masters from 
the north these new employers a church group formed to help 
exslaves may seem more benevolent at first but their rule 
becomes just as tyrannical 
the action takes place on a gray utilitarian setting by charles 
mcclennahan its simple but effective allowing the fastmoving 
action to unfold quickly and with a minimum of fuss 
in many ways fullers plays tackle the same themes as august 
wilsons joe turners come and gone the story of exslaves 
coming to terms with their past wilsons drama contains some 
haunting and painful but strangely beautiful images sally and 
prince paint much more literal pictures well have to wait for 
the next three plays to see if fullers vision is more fully 
realized 
</TEXT>
