<TEXT>
patients at inge kemp genefkes clinic 
for torture victims say their injuries often were inflicted in the 
presence of doctors nurses or psychologists people trained to 
heal 
the danish physician said it has become clear during six years of 
treating battered refugees and studying torture cases that medical 
personnel nearly always were involved even if only giving tacit 
assent 
in a welldocumented case in uruguay a prison psychologist 
advised torturers on how to break victims 
studies by the clinic indicate up to 25000 people in the medical 
profession are involved 
torture could not take place to the extent it does today if 
doctors were not implicated the doctor said these doctors 
should be thrown out of medical organizations and not only in their 
own country 
dr genefke is director of the international rehabilitation and 
research center for torture victims it treats victims publishes 
educational material trains doctors and psychologists in the care 
of victims and conducts courses for police and others who deal with 
refugees 
it is private and independent financed by the government and 
private donations 
her study of torture started 15 years ago when dr genefke was 
in a group of physicians asked by the amnesty international human 
rights group to examine victims for evidence of torture 
she opened the center in 1982 in a wing of university hospital in 
copenhagen and has helped establish similar facilities in the united 
states the philippines norway and elsewhere the copenhagen clinic 
has a staff of 30 doctors psychologists and others who treat 70100 
victims and families every year 
the 1988 right livelihood award was given to dr genefke baron 
jakob von uexkull established the prize in 1980 for humanitarian 
work 
estimates by the center indicate 30 percent of the approximately 
24000 people given asylum in denmark have been exposed to torture 
we used to believe that medical personnel participating in 
torture was a rare phenomenon but now we know that almost all 
torture victims have been in contact with them in the actual torture 
process said peter vesti a staff psychiatrist 
today we know the purpose of torture is not to get information 
but to destroy the personality and spread terror to control the 
population 
in 1986 the center broadened its scope to include research and 
documentation on torture in cooperation with doctors in latin 
america and europe 
an international committee has been formed to expose illegal 
practices and revoke licenses of doctors involved with torture 
amnesty international has estimated torture is practiced in at least 
90 countries 
in uruguay and in chile the medical associations have been 
extremely brave and courageous dr genefke said 
several hundred military doctors are believed involved in torture 
in each of those countries the center has reported dr francisco 
rivas former director of chiles medical association told the 
associated press in santiago four doctors had been expelled and two 
suspended from membership 
they are a really astounding example of how national medical 
associations can deal with this issue eric stover of the american 
association for the advancement of science said in a telephone 
interview 
not only have they disciplined physicians while the pinochet 
government is in power they have adopted a set of guidelines for 
physicians 
stover said chiles was a unique case of a medical association 
acting against doctors involved in torture while a military 
government remained in power 
in uruguay where democracy was restored in 1985 the ethics 
board of the physicians union imposed sanctions on four doctors 
including eduardo saiz found to have issued a death certificate in 
1984 that concealed evidence of torture 
all four continue practicing medicine in uruguay however about 
200 doctors have given depositions about their activities under the 
military dictatorship that began in 1973 but action has been taken 
only against saiz and the other three 
in brazil last march the regional council of medicine revoked 
the license of amilcar lobo an army doctor who attended torture 
sessions in 19701974 brazilian press reports say lobo has 
implicated other doctors but no formal charges have resulted 
emilie trautmann of amnesty international said the turkish 
medical association was investigating charges in that country 
dr genefke said the involvement of medical people in torture can 
take many forms for example a doctor can examine a prisoner and 
conclude that he or she has a weak heart and should not have 
electrical torture because they are not supposed to die 
she also said psychological torture often involving threats can 
be worse than physical punishment 
her center has done extensive research on torture methods in 
order to develop the most effective medical and psychological care 
for victims most are treated as outpatients 
treatment at the center combines physiotherapy psychotheraphy 
and social counseling it usually lasts 10 to 12 months 
the clinic decor is cheerful and the atmosphere friendly beige 
and yellow furniture and flowered textiles are used to reduce the 
resemblance to a medical institution 
patients report such tortures as hanging by hands or elbows 
sometimes for days electric shocks beatings amd holding the head 
under filthy water 
long afterward patients often have such symptoms as sexual 
disturbance hallucinations fear confusion nightmares and loss of 
selfconfidence and selfrespect vesti said 
as dr genefke explained it there is so much fear anger 
aggressions shame and guilt that has to be expressed and it is 
very very difficult we dont call our patients torture victims we 
call them torture survivors 
</TEXT>
