<TEXT>
almost from the minute he takes the presidential oath jan 20 
george bush will face a raft of fastdeveloping foreign policy 
issues in a world that has changed radically from the one ronald 
reagan found eight years before 
most immediately pressing perhaps is the middle east where the 
united states could be on the verge of its first major involvement 
in a peace effort since henry a kissingers shuttle diplomacy of 
the 1970s 
mikhail s gorbachevs changing soviet union and more ussoviet 
arms agreements also are likely items on the agenda for the early 
days of the bush presidency 
then there is china and its new contacts with moscow europe 
where the east is at a crossroads and the west looks with less 
trepidation toward the soviet bloc latin america with its debt and 
economic stagnation africa where south african apartheid remains a 
troublesome and delicate issue for the white house and asia where 
burgeoning economies still pour goods into main street usa 
even the south pacific the place people dream of for tranquil 
escape has become a piece in the world chess game 
each year at this time the associated press asks its 
correspondents in strategic areas of the world to look ahead to what 
americans can expect abroad in the new year 
for 1989 they were asked to look ahead to what president bush 
can expect in his first year in office 
these are their reports 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
george bush inherits a rapidly changing 
climate in the middle east where a us dialogue with the plo holds 
the seeds of a possible breakthrough in settling the arabisraeli 
conflict 
the reagan administrations decision dec 14 to talk to the 
palestine liberation organization after its chairman yasser arafat 
said the plo recognized israels right to exist and renounced 
terrorism will give bush the opportunity to make a significant 
impact on the longstalled peace process 
whatever the outcome of the usplo dialogue it will put 
pressure on israel appalled at the us decision to negotiate with 
the plo on the creation of a palestinian state declared in the 
occupied west bank and gaza strip by the plos parliamentinexile 
with israel increasingly isolated bush could be in a position to 
encourage prime minister yitzhak shamir to be more flexible but 
there will likely be hard bargaining amid arab soviet and european 
pressure for an international peace conference attended by the plo 
bush will also find new possibilities for resuming relations with 
iran under the islamic republics developing opendoor policy of 
improving its ties with the rest of the world ending nine years of 
political isolation 
that could improve the prospects of freeing western hostages in 
lebanon most of the 16 foreigners including nine americans are 
held by proiranian shiite moslem extremists 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in less than four years mikhail s gorbachev has 
painted over the image of the soviet union as a boastful 
missilewielding totalitarian state with a portrait of a hopeful 
giant struggling to pull itself up by the bootstraps and join the 
community of peaceful nations 
but the soviet union still has those missiles and if president 
bush is to continue a period of easing world tensions he must find 
some way to break the deadlock that prevented his predecessor from 
signing an agreement with gorbachev to slash strategic arsenals in 
half 
the initial roadblock remains president reagans star wars 
program to develop a spacebased defense against missile attack 
gorbachev insists such a program only opens a new dangerous arena 
for the arms race and makes reductions in offensive weapons 
impossible beyond that lie unresolved questions about how the two 
sides can fairly balance reductions in their inherently different 
land sea and air weapons systems 
gorbachev is busy not only trying to restructure the economy and 
way of thinking in his own country but he also is trying to break 
down eastwest barriers and develop new trade relationships 
throughout the world the united states has moved more slowly than 
some nations in asia and western europe to encourage an end to 
soviet isolation and support development of a potentially powerful 
new soviet market 
