relations particularly with west germany could weaken us ties to 
its nato partners as gorbachev works to build what he calls a 
common european home 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in eastern europe george bush 
faces a delicate balancing act between communist authorities opening 
up to reform and the increasingly vocal and active independent 
groups who want the west to insist on more human rights 
as in the soviet union communist governments in hungary poland 
czechoslovakia and bulgaria are realizing they must open up to 
economic and perhaps political reform in order to modernize outmoded 
industry and keep consumer demands satisfied 
east germany and romania for the time being have rejected any 
need for the change their allies have embraced with varying degrees 
of enthusiasm 
but new laws allowing more private and foreign investment in east 
bloc economies will not boost output unless the west agrees to make 
large loans and import or sell its advanced technology 
some west european leaders have talked of a kind of marshall 
plan to help out eastern europe where massive investment would be 
needed to provide modern housing and industry and clean up the 
heavily polluted environment 
but independent groups encouraged by president mikhail s 
gorbachevs reforms in the soviet union are also placing increasing 
demands for genuine democracy 
us trade with eastern europe traditionally has been small but 
bush will have a voice in determining the stand of allies like west 
germany with significant business activities in the east as they 
try to juggle the demands of communists for more money and activists 
for a firm stand on human rights 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
presidentelect bush will find a western 
europe preoccupied with contentious arms control talks efforts to 
