most tolls on the st lawrence seaway will 
increase by 45 percent in each of the next two years officials of 
the binational waterway said tuesday 
the higher tolls being levied in 1989 and 1990 are needed to help 
the system keep pace with inflation said us seaway administrator 
james l emery and william a oneil president of the seaway 
authority of canada 
however tolls for humanitarianaid shipments will be eliminated 
and lumber shipments will be reclassified as bulk cargo and 
therefore have a lower toll officials said these moves are 
intended to spur increased movement of those two cargos 
the combined toll for general cargo on the seaway in 1989 is 
286 per metric ton while the rate for bulk cargo is 133 per ton 
to be qualify for the lower rate the lumber must be timber or 
logs sawed or split and rough or dressed into various sizes for use 
as beams joists rafters studs boards of planks 
there is an abundance of forest land and wood product 
industries in the western great lakes region oneil said the 
seaway is a natural transportation route for this virtually untapped 
market 
