western industrialized nations are likely to 
experience moderately low inflation rates over the next two years 
but the threat of accelerated inflation and higher interest rates is 
just over the horizon the oecd said tuesday 
in the latest issue of its semiannual economic outlook the 
secretariat of the organization for economic cooperation and 
development suggested that some tightening of fiscal policy as well 
as monetary policy may be necessary in most countries to combat 
inflationary pressures 
the secretariat also predicted that the currentaccount trade 
deficits of the three biggest oecd countries the united states 
japan and west germany will remain unacceptably high 
the parisbased oecd cautioned that although there appears to be 
no imminent problem it would be unwise to conclude that external 
trade imbalances no longer represent an important threat to 
international financial stability 
the report says the real or inflationadjusted rate of 
expansion of western industrialized economies is likely to slow to 
between 25 percent and 3 percent in 1990 from 325 percent next 
year the expansion rate this year was 4 percent 
growth in the united states is expected to slow to 25 percent in 
1990 from 3 percent in 1989 and 375 percent this year 
the oecd also suggested that the dollar may strengthen against 
