pillsbury co said tuesday its profit fell 38 
percent in its second quarter and 10 percent for the first half of 
its fiscal year due to the costs of its unsuccessful battle against 
hostile suitor grand metropolitan plc 
pillsbury said its net income in the three months ended nov 30 
totaled 448 million or 52 cents per share compared with 725 
million or 84 cents per share in the same period a year ago sales 
rose to 175 billion from 169 billion 
the food and restaurant company agreed sunday to accept a 
sweetened 568 billion takeover bid from the british conglomerate 
which had made its first offer on oct 4 
pillsbury said the profit decline was due to a substantial 
onetime investment in the burger king advertising fund and the cost 
of responding to grand mets takeover bid 
the burger king investment reduced net earnings by 144 million 
or 17 cents per share in the quarter while aftertax costs related 
to the tender offer totaled 132 million or 15 cents per share 
the company said 
operating profit for restaurants fell to 42 million in the 
quarter from 476 million a year ago included in the latest 
quarters results was a onetime investment of 234 million to 
reduce the deficit in burger kings advertising fund 
pillsburys foods businesses reported operating profit of 1328 
million for the quarter a 16 percent gain from the yearearlier 
period 
